			<div type="bibliography">
				<!--ASB 1960: 22. —Aung Thaw 1972: 32. — Sircar 1975-76: 210-217. —Sein Maung Oo 1993: 134-5. — Gutman 2001: 109 n. 1. — Griffiths 2015: 282 n. 1 [2].-->
				<!--[Todo: markup citedRange elements if necessary]-->
				<p><bibl><ptr target="bib:ASB"/><citedRange>1960:
					22</citedRange></bibl> (in Burmese), reports the discovery of a single
					fragment of a brick with three lines of Sanskrit. <bibl><ptr target="bib:SeinMaungOo1968_01"/><citedRange>183</citedRange></bibl> (also in Burmese), ( = <bibl><ptr target="bib:SeinMaungOo1993"/><citedRange>134-5</citedRange></bibl>) reiterates much of the ASB report. <bibl><ptr target="bib:AungThaw1972_01"/><citedRange>32</citedRange></bibl> mentions several (more) fragments of a Sanskrit inscription discovered in 1970. These (5) fragments (not including the one reported in ASB) were edited by <bibl><ptr target="bib:Sircar1975-1976_01"/><citedRange>210-217</citedRange></bibl>. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Gutman2001"/><citedRange>109 n. 1</citedRange></bibl> considers the significance of the name <foreign>Kalaśapura</foreign> that appears several times in later fragments, and <bibl><ptr target="bib:Griffiths2015"/><citedRange>282, n. 1 [2]</citedRange></bibl>, argues that the ASB and the Sircar fragments originally belonged to a single large inscription.</p>
